It then calculates the total size of all packages and initializes the minimum wasted space to a large value. Remember that, the result needs to be returned modulo 1e9 + 7.
Iterating through the suppliers (boxes), it sorts the box sizes in non-decreasing order and checks if the largest box can contain the largest package. If not, we move on to the next supplier.
For each supplier, we iterate through their box sizes and for each box, we use binary search (upper_bound for C++ and bisect_right for Python) to find the first package that does not fit in the box. We then update the wasted space with the box size minus the largest package size that could fit in that box.
After iterating through all the suppliers, we return the minimum wasted space added to the total size of packages. If none of the suppliers can fit all the packages, we return -1.
